IMPORT io

' bug-366 (modelling half): `Money * Float` needs the ERR_INVALID_FORMAT message
' object for the same reason `Float * Fixed` does — the spec gives a non-finite
' Float operand the same ErrInvalidFormat failure (77050003) when it is consumed
' into an exact type. The predicate only asked whether the result was `Fixed`, so
' every Money-with-Float expression under-reported and its module aborted with
' "has no data object".
'
' This half needs no record field: it fails with plain locals, which is exactly
' why it is a separate fixture from the seam half. Keep the module free of any
' Float-into-Fixed expression, which would turn the message on by that route.
'
' The `f` suffixes are deliberate: a bare decimal scaling a Money warns
' MONEY_INEXACT_FLOAT_LITERAL, and `f` is how the language says "the Float is
' intentional" — which it is, since a Float operand is the whole subject here.
FUNC applyRate(amount AS Money, rate AS Float) AS Money
  RETURN amount * rate
END FUNC

FUNC main AS Integer
  io::print(toString(applyRate(10.00m, 2.5)))
  io::print(toString(3.0f * 4.00m))
  io::print(toString(10.00m / 4.0f))
  RETURN 0
END FUNC
